\subsection{Counterspells}
\label{magic:counterspells}
\index{spells!counterspells}
\index{counterspells}

An entities Magic Resistance can be increased by the use of a
counterspell.

Counterspells act to defeat the workings of other spells cast by
members of the specific college against which the counterspell is
directed.  Each college has a General Knowledge Counterspell and a
Special Knowledge Counterspell.  These are specific to the college --
a Special Fire College counterspell will not affect the workings of a
Special Earth College spell, nor would it affect the workings of a
Fire College General spell.  Adepts learn the counterspells affecting
their college as part of their General Knowledge upon joining the
college.

\textbf{Note:}
Counterspells are the only spells of a college other than their own
that a character can learn.  They are an exception to the general rule
that one can know only the spells of one's own college.  Counterspells
may be learnt from any Adept of that college (or a Namer) who is
willing to teach it.  As for other spells a minimum expertise is
required in a spell before it may be taught, equivalent to being of
rank 6 or above.  Members of the College of Namers specialise in
counterspells, thus giving them special benefits.  All counterspells
of colleges other than that of the character's own college may only be
practised at rank 0 (i.e.\ unranked), unless the character is a Namer, in
which case rank may be achieved.

Counterspells are always General Knowledge spells of the college to
which they pertain, but are considered Special Knowledge spells when
learnt by Adepts of other colleges and as such are effected by the
base chance modifiers of that college.  All counterspells known by
Namers are part of the General Knowledge of that college.

\subsubsection{Counterspell}

\begin{spelldesc}
\emph{Range:} 25 feet + 25 / Rank \\
\emph{Duration:} [D + 5] minutes + 1 / Rank \\
\emph{Experience Multiple:} \\
\hspace{1.5em} 100 -- General Knowledge Counterspell \\
\hspace{1.5em}  200 -- Special Knowledge Counterspell \\
\emph{Base Chance:} 40\% \\
\emph{Resist:}  May only be passively resisted \\
\emph{Storage:} Investment, Potion, Ward, Magical Trap \\
\emph{Target:} Entity or area \\
\end{spelldesc}
\emph{Effects:} A counterspell may be cast on an entity (including the
Adept) or on a area (a hex and the surrounding six hexes on the
Tactical Display).  The entity with the counterspell on, or within an
area with a counterspell on, adds 30 (+ 3 / Rank) to their Magic
Resistance, for the purposes of resisting the type of spell to which
the counterspell applies.

When a counterspell is cast over an area, in addition to the gain in
Magic Resistance, any individual occupying that area may not use a
spell of the type affected by that counterspell until they vacate the
affected area.  This is only an effect of the area counterspells --
counterspells cast on individuals do not inhibit the use of magic by
that individual.  All individuals in the area, or moving into it, add
30 (+ 3 / Rank) to their Magic Resistance until the area is vacated.
A double or triple effect can increase the size of the area (by
increasing the diameter to 25' or 35' respectively) or increase the
duration of the counterspell.

If a being or area were already under the effects of a counterspell
affecting one college, a counterspell affecting another college cast
on them would have no effect.  Rather it will ``stack'', and when the
first counterspell expires the second one will then come into effect.
Thus the maximum number of counterspells able to be protective on an
entity at once is four -- the General and Special Knowledge
Counterspells of one college on the individual, and the Special and
General Knowledge Counterspells of another college on the area in
which the person is standing.  If a higher ranked counterspell of the
same type is cast however, it will ``override'' the original, and the
entity will get the benefit from the higher ranked spell.  An entity
may never benefit from more than one counterspell against a particular
spell, that is if one has the same counterspell on ones person as on
the area currently occupied, only the highest ranked one would have an
effect (although the area spell could still inhibit spell casting).

Wards can be temporarily ``defused'' by the casting of the appropriate
counterspell, in a manner analogous to switching on a safety catch on
a gun.  The area-effect counterspell(s) must cover the whole area of
the ward.  When the duration of the counterspell(s) ends the ward
becomes active again (it does not get triggered).
\index{ward!defused}

An Adept may always counter the effect of their own spell by the
appropriate counterspell (unless otherwise specified in the spell
description).  In all other cases only spells specifically so stating
may be removed by any person by the appropriate counterspell -- for
example the Damnum Minatum (G-1 Wicca college), the Curse Spell (G-5
Rune).  For example if an entity with a Damnum Minatum on it has a
Wicca general counterspell cast upon them the spell dispels the last
Damnum Minatum put on.  The counterspell will have no other effect.
Only Namers may remove the effects of other spells, by means of the
Ritual of Dissipation (\S \ref{namer:dissipation}).  Counterspells as
used by practitioners of the College of Naming Incantations have some
additional powers -- see the college description for more details.

When an Adept attempts to remove a spell effect using a counterspell,
they must direct the counterspell at the specific spell effect.  In
the case of area effect spells, the Adept just has to place an area
counterspell within the area of the spell.  It need not cover the
entire area of the spell.  In general, this will only apply to Namers
with Dissipation, but items and special abilities may be affected.

Note that counterspells are resistible when cast at an entity, so
unless the entity is deliberately not resisting they must attempt to
resist the spell.

